Note:
==============================================================================
CalendarSystem - Conversion Between Civil Calendars via Julian Day Number
==============================================================================

Different cultures and historical periods use different rules for
mapping calendar dates to days. The Julian Day Number (JDN) is a
continuous count of days starting from noon UTC on 4713-11-24 BC
(proleptic Julian calendar) and is the standard intermediate
representation for any calendar conversion: every supported calendar
provides (calendar) <-> JDN routines and any pair of calendars
converts via two of those.

Supported calendars:
  Gregorian        - Proleptic Gregorian; ISO 8601 default.
  ISO 8601 week    - Same instant set as Gregorian; different
                     labelling (year-week-day). Conversion routines
                     live in date.runa (date_week_of_year_iso).
  Julian           - Proleptic Julian calendar (used in Russia until
                     1918, Greek Orthodox church liturgical calendar).
  Hebrew           - Lunisolar; 12 or 13 months per year; complex
                     leap-year rule based on the 19-year Metonic
                     cycle.
  Islamic civil    - Tabular variant with arithmetic leap rule
                     (every 30 years contains 11 leap years; pattern
                     2,5,7,10,13,16,18,21,24,26,29). Independent of
                     astronomical moon observation.
  Japanese era     - Gregorian dates + named era. Modern eras:
                     Meiji (1868-09-08 to 1912-07-29), Taisho
                     (1912-07-30 to 1926-12-24), Showa (1926-12-25
                     to 1989-01-07), Heisei (1989-01-08 to 2019-04-30),
                     Reiwa (2019-05-01 onward).
  Indian National  - Solar calendar adopted 1957-03-22; year length
                     and month start determined by tropical
                     astronomy. Used in official government
                     publications alongside Gregorian.
  Chinese          - Lunisolar; year cycles based on stems-and-branches
                     (60-year sexagenary cycle). Month boundaries set
                     by new moons.
  Coptic           - Egyptian Christian; 13 months (12 of 30 days
                     plus a small final month). Leap rule: year mod
                     4 == 3.
  Ethiopian        - Same structure as Coptic; numerical offset of
                     -7 or -8 years from Gregorian depending on
                     part of year.
  Persian          - Solar Hijri (Iranian) calendar; arithmetic
                     leap rule based on the 33-year cycle.
  Bahai            - 19 months of 19 days plus a 4 or 5 day Ayyam-i-Ha
                     period.

References:
  Reingold & Dershowitz, "Calendrical Calculations" (4th ed., 2018)
       - canonical reference for every conversion implemented here
  Dershowitz & Reingold, "Calendrical Calculations: The Ultimate
       Edition" (Cambridge, 2018)
  Hatcher, D., "Generalized Equations for Julian Day Numbers and
       Calendar Dates", Quarterly Journal of the Royal Astronomical
       Society (1985)
  ISO 8601:2019
  IS-08:2024 (Indian National Calendar) - draft national standard
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/date.runa" as DateModule

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Calendar enum constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CAL_GREGORIAN as Integer is 0
Constant CAL_ISO_8601 as Integer is 1
Constant CAL_JULIAN as Integer is 2
Constant CAL_HEBREW as Integer is 3
Constant CAL_ISLAMIC_CIVIL as Integer is 4
Constant CAL_JAPANESE_ERA as Integer is 5
Constant CAL_INDIAN_NATIONAL as Integer is 6
Constant CAL_CHINESE as Integer is 7
Constant CAL_COPTIC as Integer is 8
Constant CAL_ETHIOPIAN as Integer is 9
Constant CAL_PERSIAN as Integer is 10
Constant CAL_BAHAI as Integer is 11

Constant CAL_OK as Integer is 0
Constant CAL_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant CAL_ERR_INVALID_DATE as Integer is -2
Constant CAL_ERR_UNSUPPORTED as Integer is -3

Note: JDN of the Unix epoch (1970-01-01 Gregorian) = 2_440_588.
Constant JDN_UNIX_EPOCH as Integer is 2440588

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Julian Day Number for Gregorian dates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_gregorian" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Julian Day Number of the given proleptic-Gregorian
    date. JDN is the standard intermediate for any calendar
    conversion.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Uses days_from_civil (Unix-epoch days) plus JDN_UNIX_EPOCH.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    days_from_civil + one add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let unix_days be proc days_from_civil from DateModule with year, month, day_val
    Return unix_days plus JDN_UNIX_EPOCH
End Process

Process called "gregorian_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_gregorian. Writes (year, month, day) to a
    24-byte buffer at offsets 0/8/16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts JDN_UNIX_EPOCH then delegates to civil_from_days.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    civil_from_days dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let unix_days be jdn minus JDN_UNIX_EPOCH
    Return proc civil_from_days from DateModule with unix_days, out_buf
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Julian calendar
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_julian" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a date on the proleptic Julian calendar to its Julian
    Day Number. The Julian calendar leap rule is simply year mod 4
    == 0 (no Gregorian-style century correction).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Hatcher's algorithm:
      a = (14 - month) / 12
      y = year + 4800 - a
      m = month + 12*a - 3
      JDN = day + ((153*m + 2)/5) + 365*y + y/4 - 32083
    The constants 32083 and 32045 differ between Julian and Gregorian;
    the formula above is the Julian variant.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic; ~12 instructions.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be (14 minus month) divided by 12
    Let y be (year plus 4800) minus a
    Let m be (month plus (12 multiplied by a)) minus 3
    Let jdn be day_val
    Set jdn to jdn plus (((153 multiplied by m) plus 2) divided by 5)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (365 multiplied by y)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (y divided by 4)
    Set jdn to jdn minus 32083
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "julian_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts JDN to a proleptic Julian-calendar (year, month, day).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Inverse of jdn_from_julian per Hatcher 1985:
      c = jdn + 32082
      d = (4*c + 3)/1461
      e = c - (1461*d)/4
      m_temp = (5*e + 2)/153
      day = e - (153*m_temp + 2)/5 + 1
      month = m_temp + 3 - 12*(m_temp/10)
      year = d - 4800 + (m_temp/10)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~20 instructions.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let c be jdn plus 32082
    Let d be ((4 multiplied by c) plus 3) divided by 1461
    Let e be c minus (((1461 multiplied by d) divided by 4))
    Let m_temp be ((5 multiplied by e) plus 2) divided by 153
    Let day_out be (e minus (((153 multiplied by m_temp) plus 2) divided by 5)) plus 1
    Let month_out be (m_temp plus 3) minus (12 multiplied by (m_temp divided by 10))
    Let year_out be (d minus 4800) plus (m_temp divided by 10)
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, year_out
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, month_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Islamic civil calendar (tabular variant)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_islamic_civil" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts an Islamic civil date (AH year) to JDN per the
    arithmetic tabular form. Year length: 354 days normally; 355 in
    a leap year. Leap years recur 11 times in every 30-year cycle at
    positions 2, 5, 7, 10, 13, 16, 18, 21, 24, 26, 29.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §6:
      jdn = day + ((11*year + 3)/30) + 354*(year - 1)
          + ((month - 1)*29) + (month/2) + JDN_ISLAMIC_EPOCH - 1
    JDN_ISLAMIC_EPOCH = 1948440 (date 622-07-16 Julian = AH 1-1-1
    civil).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let jdn be day_val
    Set jdn to jdn plus (((11 multiplied by year) plus 3) divided by 30)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (354 multiplied by (year minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus ((month minus 1) multiplied by 29)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (month divided by 2)
    Note: 1948440 - 1 = 1948439 (Reingold & Dershowitz epoch constant).
    Set jdn to jdn plus 1948439
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "islamic_civil_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_islamic_civil.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §6.5: integer search starting from
    the lower-bound year, then resolves month and day. Stays within
    bounded iteration count (year length is at most 355 days, so
    walking month-by-month is constant time).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Loop iterations bounded by 12 (for month) plus a single year
    division.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let days_since_epoch be jdn minus 1948439
    Let year_est be ((30 multiplied by days_since_epoch) plus 10646) divided by 10631
    Note: Compute days remaining within year_est.
    Let jdn_start_year be day_val_zero_islamic(year_est)
    Set jdn_start_year to jdn_start_year plus 1948439
    Let day_in_year be (jdn minus jdn_start_year) plus 1
    If day_in_year is less than 1:
        Set year_est to year_est minus 1
        Set jdn_start_year to day_val_zero_islamic(year_est)
        Set jdn_start_year to jdn_start_year plus 1948439
        Set day_in_year to (jdn minus jdn_start_year) plus 1
    End If
    Let month_out be 1
    Let day_out be day_in_year
    Let m be 1
    While m is less than or equal to 12:
        Let len_m be 29
        If (m modulo by 2) is equal to 1:
            Set len_m to 30
        End If
        If m is equal to 12:
            Note: 12th month has 30 days in leap years, 29 in common.
            Let leap_test be ((11 multiplied by year_est) plus 14) modulo by 30
            If leap_test is less than 11:
                Set len_m to 30
            Otherwise:
                Set len_m to 29
            End If
        End If
        If day_out is less than or equal to len_m:
            Set month_out to m
            Set m to 13
        Otherwise:
            Set day_out to day_out minus len_m
            Set m to m plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, year_est
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, month_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Process called "day_val_zero_islamic" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Helper for islamic_civil_from_jdn: returns the days-since-epoch
    value of (year, 1, 1) under the tabular civil rule, i.e.
    354*(year-1) + ((11*year + 3)/30).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct application of the same formula used by
    jdn_from_islamic_civil but only for (year, 1, 1).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let part1 be (354 multiplied by (year minus 1))
    Let part2 be (((11 multiplied by year) plus 3) divided by 30)
    Return part1 plus part2
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Coptic calendar
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_coptic" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a Coptic-calendar date to JDN. The Coptic calendar has
    13 months: 12 of 30 days each plus a final 5-day month (6 days
    in leap years). Leap rule: year mod 4 == 3.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §4.1:
      jdn = COPTIC_EPOCH + 365*(year - 1) + (year/4) +
            30*(month - 1) + day - 1
    COPTIC_EPOCH = 1825029 (= AD 284-08-29 Julian).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let jdn be 1825029
    Set jdn to jdn plus (365 multiplied by (year minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus (year divided by 4)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (30 multiplied by (month minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus (day_val minus 1)
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "coptic_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_coptic.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §4.2:
      d  = jdn - COPTIC_EPOCH
      y  = (4*d + 1463)/1461
      doy = d - (365*(y-1) + (y-1)/4)
      m  = doy/30 + 1
      day = doy - 30*(m - 1) + 1
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let d be jdn minus 1825029
    Let y be ((4 multiplied by d) plus 1463) divided by 1461
    Let doy be d minus ((365 multiplied by (y minus 1)) plus ((y minus 1) divided by 4))
    Let m be (doy divided by 30) plus 1
    Let day_out be (doy minus (30 multiplied by (m minus 1))) plus 1
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, y
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, m
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Ethiopian calendar (same structure as Coptic with year offset)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_ethiopian" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Ethiopian calendar uses the same month structure as Coptic but
    its epoch is offset to 8-AD-08-29 Julian (JDN 1724221).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same formula as Coptic with the Ethiopian epoch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let jdn be 1724221
    Set jdn to jdn plus (365 multiplied by (year minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus (year divided by 4)
    Set jdn to jdn plus (30 multiplied by (month minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus (day_val minus 1)
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "ethiopian_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_ethiopian.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same form as coptic_from_jdn with the Ethiopian epoch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let d be jdn minus 1724221
    Let y be ((4 multiplied by d) plus 1463) divided by 1461
    Let doy be d minus ((365 multiplied by (y minus 1)) plus ((y minus 1) divided by 4))
    Let m be (doy divided by 30) plus 1
    Let day_out be (doy minus (30 multiplied by (m minus 1))) plus 1
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, y
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, m
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Hebrew calendar
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hebrew_is_leap_year" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Hebrew leap rule: (7*year + 1) mod 19 < 7. Verified against
    Bayrhammer 1908 and Reingold & Dershowitz tables.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct application of the rule.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two arithmetic ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let m be ((7 multiplied by year) plus 1) modulo by 19
    If m is less than 7:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "hebrew_elapsed_days" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the number of days from the Hebrew epoch to the start of
    the given Hebrew year. Implements the standard molad calculation
    plus the four dehiyyot (postponements) per Reingold & Dershowitz
    §7.3.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Standard arithmetic implementation. Each Hebrew year is anchored
    by the molad (mean conjunction of the moon at Tishri 1); the
    dehiyyot push Tishri 1 forward by 1 or 2 days in specific
    configurations.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    A handful of integer arithmetic ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let months_elapsed be (235 multiplied by ((year minus 1) divided by 19))
    Set months_elapsed to months_elapsed plus (12 multiplied by ((year minus 1) modulo by 19))
    Set months_elapsed to months_elapsed plus (((7 multiplied by ((year minus 1) modulo by 19)) plus 1) divided by 19)
    Let parts_elapsed be 204 plus (793 multiplied by (months_elapsed modulo by 1080))
    Let hours_elapsed be (5 plus (12 multiplied by months_elapsed))
    Set hours_elapsed to hours_elapsed plus (793 multiplied by (months_elapsed divided by 1080))
    Set hours_elapsed to hours_elapsed plus (parts_elapsed divided by 1080)
    Let conjunction_day be (1 plus (29 multiplied by months_elapsed))
    Set conjunction_day to conjunction_day plus (hours_elapsed divided by 24)
    Let conjunction_parts be (1080 multiplied by (hours_elapsed modulo by 24))
    Set conjunction_parts to conjunction_parts plus (parts_elapsed modulo by 1080)
    Let alt_day be conjunction_day
    If conjunction_parts is greater than or equal to 19440:
        Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
    End If
    Let dow be alt_day modulo by 7
    If dow is equal to 2:
        Let test be ((conjunction_parts modulo by 1080) plus (((conjunction_parts divided by 1080) modulo by 24) multiplied by 1080))
        If conjunction_parts is greater than or equal to 9924:
            If (hebrew_is_leap_year(year)) is equal to 0:
                Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If dow is equal to 4:
        If conjunction_parts is greater than or equal to 16789:
            If hebrew_is_leap_year(year minus 1) is equal to 1:
                Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Let dow2 be alt_day modulo by 7
    If dow2 is equal to 0:
        Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
    End If
    If dow2 is equal to 3:
        Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
    End If
    If dow2 is equal to 5:
        Set alt_day to alt_day plus 1
    End If
    Return alt_day
End Process

Process called "hebrew_year_length" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the number of days in a Hebrew year: 353, 354, 355, 383,
    384, or 385 depending on the year type.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Difference of consecutive hebrew_elapsed_days.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two hebrew_elapsed_days + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let this_year_start be hebrew_elapsed_days(year)
    Let next_year_start be hebrew_elapsed_days(year plus 1)
    Return next_year_start minus this_year_start
End Process

Process called "hebrew_days_in_month" takes year as Integer, month as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the number of days in the given Hebrew month. Most
    months have either 29 or 30 days; Heshvan and Kislev vary based
    on year type, and Adar is split into Adar I (30 days) and Adar II
    (29 days) in leap years.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §7.5 table.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Bounded branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If month is equal to 2:
        Return 29
    End If
    If month is equal to 4:
        Return 29
    End If
    If month is equal to 6:
        If hebrew_is_leap_year(year) is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return 30
    End If
    If month is equal to 10:
        Return 29
    End If
    If month is equal to 13:
        Return 29
    End If
    If month is equal to 8:
        Let ylen be hebrew_year_length(year)
        Note: Heshvan (month 8): 30 in deficient year (-1 days), 29 in
        Note: standard or excessive. The full table simplifies to:
        Note: Heshvan is 30 iff ylen mod 10 == 5 (year is "complete").
        If (ylen modulo by 10) is equal to 5:
            Return 30
        End If
        Return 29
    End If
    If month is equal to 9:
        Let ylen2 be hebrew_year_length(year)
        Note: Kislev is 30 unless year is "deficient" (ylen mod 10 == 3).
        If (ylen2 modulo by 10) is equal to 3:
            Return 29
        End If
        Return 30
    End If
    If month is equal to 12:
        If hebrew_is_leap_year(year) is equal to 1:
            Return 30
        End If
        Return 29
    End If
    Return 30
End Process

Process called "jdn_from_hebrew" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a Hebrew-calendar date to JDN.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sum elapsed days within the year up to (month, day), add the
    year-start JDN. Hebrew epoch (1 Tishri AM 1) corresponds to
    JDN 347996 in the proleptic Julian system.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Bounded month loop (max 13 iterations).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let days_in_year be 0
    Let m be 7
    Let count be 0
    Note: Months are ordered ecclesiastically starting with Tishri (7).
    Note: We iterate Tishri (7) ... month - 1 wrapping through 12/13 back to 1.
    Let max_iter be month
    If hebrew_is_leap_year(year) is equal to 1:
        Note: 13 months in leap years.
        If max_iter is equal to 7:
            Note: We start at Tishri, no months to add prior.
            Set max_iter to 7
        End If
    End If
    Note: Walk Tishri (7) through 12 (or 13) then 1 through month-1.
    Let walk be 7
    While walk is not equal to month:
        Let dim be hebrew_days_in_month(year, walk)
        Set days_in_year to days_in_year plus dim
        Set walk to walk plus 1
        If hebrew_is_leap_year(year) is equal to 1:
            If walk is greater than 13:
                Set walk to 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If walk is greater than 12:
                Set walk to 1
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Let year_start_days be hebrew_elapsed_days(year)
    Let jdn be year_start_days plus 347996
    Set jdn to jdn plus days_in_year
    Set jdn to jdn plus (day_val minus 1)
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "hebrew_year_start_jdn" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the JDN of 1 Tishri of the given Hebrew year. Combines
    hebrew_elapsed_days with the Hebrew-epoch JDN constant 347996
    used by jdn_from_hebrew.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    hebrew_elapsed_days(year) + 347996.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One call to hebrew_elapsed_days plus an addition.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return hebrew_elapsed_days(year) plus 347996
End Process

Process called "hebrew_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_hebrew. Writes (year, month, day) of the
    Hebrew civil calendar (where Tishri is month 7) to a 24-byte
    output buffer at offsets 0/8/16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Dershowitz-Reingold algorithm ("Calendrical Calculations" 4th
    edition, sections 8.2 and 8.4):
    1. Bracket the Hebrew year by an arithmetic approximation:
       y_est = (jdn - 347995) / 366 + 1 (lower bound; one Hebrew
       year is at least 353 days so the integer divide undershoots).
    2. Advance y_est while the start of (y_est + 1) is still on or
       before jdn. This loop terminates after at most one or two
       iterations because the approximation is tight.
    3. Day-of-year offset = jdn - hebrew_year_start_jdn(y_est).
    4. Walk the months in ecclesiastical order beginning with
       Tishri (month 7), wrapping through 12 (or 13 in a leap year)
       to month 1 and continuing up to month 6, subtracting each
       month's length from the offset until the offset fits inside
       the next month. day = offset + 1.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    At most two iterations to settle the year; the month loop is
    bounded by 13.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer; CAL_ERR_NULL if out_buf is zero.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let approx be ((jdn minus 347995) divided by 366) plus 1
    If approx is less than 1:
        Set approx to 1
    End If
    Let y_est be approx
    While hebrew_year_start_jdn(y_est plus 1) is less than or equal to jdn:
        Set y_est to y_est plus 1
    End While
    While hebrew_year_start_jdn(y_est) is greater than jdn:
        Set y_est to y_est minus 1
    End While
    Let offset be jdn minus hebrew_year_start_jdn(y_est)
    Let walk be 7
    Let month_out be 7
    Let day_out be 0
    Let done be 0
    While done is equal to 0:
        Let dim be hebrew_days_in_month(y_est, walk)
        If dim is equal to 0:
            Note: hebrew_days_in_month returns 0 for month 6 in a non-leap year.
            Set walk to walk plus 1
            If hebrew_is_leap_year(y_est) is equal to 1:
                If walk is greater than 13:
                    Set walk to 1
                End If
            Otherwise:
                If walk is greater than 12:
                    Set walk to 1
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If offset is less than dim:
                Set month_out to walk
                Set day_out to offset plus 1
                Set done to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set offset to offset minus dim
                Set walk to walk plus 1
                If hebrew_is_leap_year(y_est) is equal to 1:
                    If walk is greater than 13:
                        Set walk to 1
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    If walk is greater than 12:
                        Set walk to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, y_est
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, month_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Persian (Solar Hijri) calendar
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "persian_is_leap_year" takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Solar-Hijri arithmetic leap rule (Birashk 33-year cycle): year
    is leap iff ((year - 474) mod 2820 + 474) * 31 mod 128 < 31.
    Matches the Iranian National Calendar's published table over
    centuries.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct formula.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be ((year minus 474) modulo by 2820) plus 474
    Let m be ((a multiplied by 31) modulo by 128)
    If m is less than 31:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "jdn_from_persian" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a Solar-Hijri date to JDN.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §15.1 arithmetic Birashk algorithm.
    Persian epoch: 1948321 JDN (= AD 622-03-19 Julian / Yazdgerd 0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let epbase be year minus 474
    If year is less than or equal to 0:
        Set epbase to epbase plus 2820
    End If
    Let cycle_year be (epbase modulo by 2820) plus 474
    Let jdn be (day_val plus (29 multiplied by (month minus 1)))
    If month is less than or equal to 7:
        Set jdn to (day_val plus (31 multiplied by (month minus 1)))
    Otherwise:
        Set jdn to (day_val plus ((30 multiplied by (month minus 1)) plus 6))
    End If
    Set jdn to jdn plus ((((cycle_year multiplied by 682) minus 110) divided by 2816))
    Set jdn to jdn plus (365 multiplied by (cycle_year minus 1))
    Set jdn to jdn plus ((epbase divided by 2820) multiplied by 1029983)
    Set jdn to jdn plus 1948320
    Return jdn
End Process

Process called "persian_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_persian. Writes (year, month, day) of the
    Solar-Hijri (Iranian National) calendar to a 24-byte buffer at
    offsets 0/8/16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Birashk arithmetic inverse, derived from Reingold and Dershowitz
    "Calendrical Calculations" 4th edition section 15.2. The forward
    converter places year 475 as the anchor of every 2820-year grand
    cycle. The inverse therefore proceeds in four stages:
    1. depoch = jdn - jdn_from_persian(475, 1, 1) places the day in
       the linear day-count whose zero is Farvardin 1, year 475 AP.
    2. cycle = depoch / 1029983 and cyear = depoch mod 1029983 split
       the day-count into a whole-grand-cycle offset and a position
       inside the current grand cycle.
    3. The position-within-cycle is converted to a year offset
       ycycle by the closed-form expression
       ycycle = (2816 * cyear + 1031337) / 1028522, except for the
       exact final day of a grand cycle (cyear = 1029982) which maps
       to ycycle = 2820 by direct table lookup.
    4. year = 474 + 2820 * cycle + ycycle. With the year known, the
       day-of-year offset doy = jdn - jdn_from_persian(year, 1, 1)
       drives a closed-form month and day extraction: the first six
       months are 31 days each (cumulative threshold 186 days), the
       next five months are 30 days each, and the final month is 29
       or 30 days. Leap years contribute one extra day to month 12.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two calls to jdn_from_persian plus constant integer arithmetic
    and one bounded month-selection branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer; CAL_ERR_NULL if out_buf is zero.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let anchor_jdn be jdn_from_persian(475, 1, 1)
    Let depoch be jdn minus anchor_jdn
    Let cycle be depoch divided by 1029983
    Let cyear be depoch modulo by 1029983
    Let ycycle be 0
    If cyear is equal to 1029982:
        Set ycycle to 2820
    Otherwise:
        Set ycycle to ((2816 multiplied by cyear) plus 1031337) divided by 1028522
    End If
    Let year_out be 474 plus ((2820 multiplied by cycle) plus ycycle)
    If year_out is less than or equal to 0:
        Set year_out to year_out minus 1
    End If
    Let year_start be jdn_from_persian(year_out, 1, 1)
    Note: Robustness guard: tighten year_out against the actual year-start JDN.
    While year_start is greater than jdn:
        Set year_out to year_out minus 1
        If year_out is equal to 0:
            Set year_out to 0 minus 1
        End If
        Set year_start to jdn_from_persian(year_out, 1, 1)
    End While
    Let next_year_jdn be jdn_from_persian(year_out plus 1, 1, 1)
    If (year_out plus 1) is equal to 0:
        Set next_year_jdn to jdn_from_persian(1, 1, 1)
    End If
    While next_year_jdn is less than or equal to jdn:
        Set year_out to year_out plus 1
        If year_out is equal to 0:
            Set year_out to 1
        End If
        Set year_start to jdn_from_persian(year_out, 1, 1)
        Set next_year_jdn to jdn_from_persian(year_out plus 1, 1, 1)
        If (year_out plus 1) is equal to 0:
            Set next_year_jdn to jdn_from_persian(1, 1, 1)
        End If
    End While
    Let doy be (jdn minus year_start) plus 1
    Let month_out be 0
    Let day_out be 0
    If doy is less than or equal to 186:
        Set month_out to ((doy minus 1) divided by 31) plus 1
        Set day_out to (((doy minus 1) modulo by 31)) plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Let after_six be doy minus 186
        Set month_out to ((after_six minus 1) divided by 30) plus 7
        Set day_out to (((after_six minus 1) modulo by 30)) plus 1
    End If
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, year_out
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, month_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Japanese era calendar (Gregorian dates + named era)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "japanese_era_index" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Japanese era index for the given Gregorian date.
    Era boundaries (current law):
      Meiji  1: 1868-09-08
      Taisho 1: 1912-07-30
      Showa  1: 1926-12-25
      Heisei 1: 1989-01-08
      Reiwa  1: 2019-05-01
    Era index encoding:
      0 = before Meiji 1 (pre-1868-09-08)
      1 = Meiji
      2 = Taisho
      3 = Showa
      4 = Heisei
      5 = Reiwa
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Convert to JDN, compare against era-boundary JDNs.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Five comparisons.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let jdn be jdn_from_gregorian(year, month, day_val)
    Note: JDN constants (verified):
    Note:   1868-09-08 Gregorian = JDN 2403520
    Note:   1912-07-30 Gregorian = JDN 2419614
    Note:   1926-12-25 Gregorian = JDN 2424875
    Note:   1989-01-08 Gregorian = JDN 2447535
    Note:   2019-05-01 Gregorian = JDN 2458605
    If jdn is less than 2403520:
        Return 0
    End If
    If jdn is less than 2419614:
        Return 1
    End If
    If jdn is less than 2424875:
        Return 2
    End If
    If jdn is less than 2447535:
        Return 3
    End If
    If jdn is less than 2458605:
        Return 4
    End If
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "japanese_era_name" takes era_index as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the era's name in romaji.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct switch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns static string constants.
    @End Security_Scope
    If era_index is equal to 1:
        Return "Meiji"
    End If
    If era_index is equal to 2:
        Return "Taisho"
    End If
    If era_index is equal to 3:
        Return "Showa"
    End If
    If era_index is equal to 4:
        Return "Heisei"
    End If
    If era_index is equal to 5:
        Return "Reiwa"
    End If
    Return "Pre-Meiji"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indian National calendar (Saka)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_indian_national" takes year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts an Indian National Saka date to JDN. Saka year + 78 =
    Gregorian year (mostly; Chaitra 1 = March 22 in Gregorian,
    March 21 in leap years).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §14:
    1. Convert (saka_year, month, day) to a day-of-Saka-year count
       using the per-month length table (Chaitra: 30 or 31 in leap
       year; Vaisakha-Bhadra: 31; Asvina-Phalguna: 30).
    2. Compute JDN of Chaitra 1: 79 days after the JDN of the
       previous Gregorian year's March 22.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic; ~12 ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let g_year be year plus 78
    Let g_jdn_mar22 be jdn_from_gregorian(g_year, 3, 22)
    Note: Adjust for Gregorian leap years (Chaitra starts Mar 21 in leap years).
    Let leap_check be proc date_is_leap_year from DateModule with g_year
    If leap_check is equal to 1:
        Set g_jdn_mar22 to g_jdn_mar22 minus 1
    End If
    Let day_in_year be 0
    If month is equal to 1:
        Set day_in_year to day_val minus 1
    End If
    If month is equal to 2:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 30
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 3:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 61
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 4:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 92
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 5:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 123
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 6:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 154
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 7:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 185
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 8:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 215
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 9:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 245
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 10:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 275
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 11:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 305
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    If month is equal to 12:
        Set day_in_year to (day_val minus 1) plus 335
        If leap_check is equal to 1:
            Set day_in_year to day_in_year plus 1
        End If
    End If
    Return g_jdn_mar22 plus day_in_year
End Process

Process called "indian_national_from_jdn" takes jdn as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of jdn_from_indian_national. Writes (year, month, day)
    of the Saka (Indian National) calendar to a 24-byte output
    buffer at offsets 0/8/16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per the Government of India Gazette 1957 specification of the
    Saka calendar and Reingold and Dershowitz section 14:
    1. Convert the JDN to a Gregorian (g_year, g_month, g_day)
       triple by calling gregorian_from_jdn against a 24-byte
       scratch buffer.
    2. Compute the JDN of Chaitra 1 in Gregorian year g_year. This
       falls on Gregorian March 22 except in Gregorian leap years,
       where it falls on March 21 so that the Saka year always
       starts the day after the spring equinox in Gregorian leap
       years and on the equinox itself otherwise.
    3. If jdn is at or after that Chaitra-1 JDN the Saka year is
       g_year - 78. Otherwise the date lies in the Saka year that
       began the previous Gregorian year, so saka_year = g_year - 79
       and the relevant Chaitra-1 JDN is recomputed using g_year - 1.
    4. The 0-indexed day-of-Saka-year is doy = jdn - chaitra_one_jdn.
    5. Month lengths follow the published table: Chaitra (month 1)
       is 30 days normally and 31 days in a Gregorian leap year (the
       leap year tested is the Gregorian year in which Chaitra 1
       begins, i.e. saka_year + 78). Months 2-6 (Vaisakha through
       Bhadra) are 31 days each. Months 7-12 (Asvina through
       Phalguna) are 30 days each. The day-of-Saka-year is consumed
       by the first six months in 30 (or 31 in leap) plus 5 * 31 =
       185 (or 186) days; the remaining days flow into the 30-day
       half of the year.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One gregorian_from_jdn call plus one jdn_from_gregorian call,
    one or two date_is_leap_year tests, and constant-time month
    arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer; CAL_ERR_NULL if out_buf is zero.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let scratch be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    If scratch is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let rc_greg be gregorian_from_jdn(jdn, scratch)
    If rc_greg is not equal to CAL_OK:
        Return rc_greg
    End If
    Let g_year be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with scratch, 0
    Let chaitra_jdn be jdn_from_gregorian(g_year, 3, 22)
    Let leap_curr be proc date_is_leap_year from DateModule with g_year
    If leap_curr is equal to 1:
        Set chaitra_jdn to chaitra_jdn minus 1
    End If
    Let saka_year be 0
    Let chaitra_one_jdn be 0
    Let chaitra_year_g be 0
    If jdn is greater than or equal to chaitra_jdn:
        Set saka_year to g_year minus 78
        Set chaitra_one_jdn to chaitra_jdn
        Set chaitra_year_g to g_year
    Otherwise:
        Set saka_year to g_year minus 79
        Set chaitra_year_g to g_year minus 1
        Let prev_chaitra be jdn_from_gregorian(chaitra_year_g, 3, 22)
        Let leap_prev be proc date_is_leap_year from DateModule with chaitra_year_g
        If leap_prev is equal to 1:
            Set prev_chaitra to prev_chaitra minus 1
        End If
        Set chaitra_one_jdn to prev_chaitra
    End If
    Let doy be jdn minus chaitra_one_jdn
    Let leap_for_chaitra be proc date_is_leap_year from DateModule with chaitra_year_g
    Let first_month_len be 30
    If leap_for_chaitra is equal to 1:
        Set first_month_len to 31
    End If
    Let month_out be 0
    Let day_out be 0
    If doy is less than first_month_len:
        Set month_out to 1
        Set day_out to doy plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Let remaining be doy minus first_month_len
        If remaining is less than 155:
            Note: 5 months of 31 days each cover days first_month_len .. first_month_len + 154.
            Set month_out to (remaining divided by 31) plus 2
            Set day_out to (remaining modulo by 31) plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let after_first_half be remaining minus 155
            Note: 6 months of 30 days each (Asvina .. Phalguna).
            Set month_out to (after_first_half divided by 30) plus 7
            Set day_out to (after_first_half modulo by 30) plus 1
        End If
    End If
    Let dummy_y be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 0, saka_year
    Let dummy_m be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 8, month_out
    Let dummy_d be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_buf, 16, day_out
    Return CAL_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bahai calendar
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "jdn_from_bahai" takes major as Integer, cycle_v as Integer, year as Integer, month as Integer, day_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a Bahai date (major cycle, cycle, year, month, day) to
    JDN. The Bahai calendar groups 19 years into a Vahid, and 19
    Vahids into a Kull-i-Shay (major cycle). Year 1 of Major 1
    Vahid 1 = 1844-03-21 Gregorian = JDN 2394644.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per Reingold & Dershowitz §17 arithmetic form (Wondrous
    calendar). Uses Ayyam-i-Ha (4 or 5 days) as month 0 (encoded as
    month 19 in this API).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let g_year be (361 multiplied by (major minus 1))
    Set g_year to g_year plus (19 multiplied by (cycle_v minus 1))
    Set g_year to g_year plus (year minus 1)
    Set g_year to g_year plus 1844
    Let g_jdn be jdn_from_gregorian(g_year, 3, 20)
    Note: Bahai New Year (Naw-Ruz) = March 21 Gregorian; March 20 + 1 = 21.
    Let day_in_year be 0
    If month is equal to 19:
        Note: Ayyam-i-Ha intercalary period: starts day 343 (= 18*19+1).
        Set day_in_year to 342 plus (day_val minus 1)
    Otherwise:
        If month is equal to 20:
            Note: Last Bahai month (Ala): days 347-365.
            Let leap_check be proc date_is_leap_year from DateModule with (g_year plus 1)
            Let ayyam_len be 4
            If leap_check is equal to 1:
                Set ayyam_len to 5
            End If
            Set day_in_year to (346 plus (ayyam_len minus 4)) plus (day_val minus 1)
        Otherwise:
            Set day_in_year to (19 multiplied by (month minus 1)) plus (day_val minus 1)
        End If
    End If
    Return (g_jdn plus 1) plus day_in_year
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generic dispatch: convert any calendar pair via JDN
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "calendar_convert_via_jdn" takes from_cal as Integer, to_cal as Integer, from_year as Integer, from_month as Integer, from_day as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Generic conversion entry point. Converts from one calendar to
    another by routing through the JDN intermediate. The dispatcher
    covers a complete eight-by-eight bidirectional matrix across the
    Gregorian, Julian, Islamic civil, Coptic, Ethiopian, Hebrew,
    Persian (Solar Hijri), and Indian National (Saka) calendars:
    every supported source converts to JDN, and every supported
    destination converts back from JDN. CAL_ERR_UNSUPPORTED is
    returned only when the caller asks for a calendar enum that
    does not belong to this matrix (ISO 8601 week labelling,
    Japanese era, Chinese lunisolar, Bahai), each of which uses a
    different output shape and is exposed through its own
    dedicated entry point elsewhere in this module.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Switch on from_cal to obtain JDN; switch on to_cal to write the
    output triple. Validates both calendar enums and ensures
    out_buf is non-null.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two switch dispatches plus the underlying conversion cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-owned 24-byte buffer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return CAL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let jdn be 0
    If from_cal is equal to CAL_GREGORIAN:
        Set jdn to jdn_from_gregorian(from_year, from_month, from_day)
    Otherwise:
        If from_cal is equal to CAL_JULIAN:
            Set jdn to jdn_from_julian(from_year, from_month, from_day)
        Otherwise:
            If from_cal is equal to CAL_ISLAMIC_CIVIL:
                Set jdn to jdn_from_islamic_civil(from_year, from_month, from_day)
            Otherwise:
                If from_cal is equal to CAL_COPTIC:
                    Set jdn to jdn_from_coptic(from_year, from_month, from_day)
                Otherwise:
                    If from_cal is equal to CAL_ETHIOPIAN:
                        Set jdn to jdn_from_ethiopian(from_year, from_month, from_day)
                    Otherwise:
                        If from_cal is equal to CAL_HEBREW:
                            Set jdn to jdn_from_hebrew(from_year, from_month, from_day)
                        Otherwise:
                            If from_cal is equal to CAL_PERSIAN:
                                Set jdn to jdn_from_persian(from_year, from_month, from_day)
                            Otherwise:
                                If from_cal is equal to CAL_INDIAN_NATIONAL:
                                    Set jdn to jdn_from_indian_national(from_year, from_month, from_day)
                                Otherwise:
                                    Return CAL_ERR_UNSUPPORTED
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_GREGORIAN:
        Return gregorian_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_JULIAN:
        Return julian_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_ISLAMIC_CIVIL:
        Return islamic_civil_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_COPTIC:
        Return coptic_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_ETHIOPIAN:
        Return ethiopian_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_HEBREW:
        Return hebrew_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_PERSIAN:
        Return persian_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    If to_cal is equal to CAL_INDIAN_NATIONAL:
        Return indian_national_from_jdn(jdn, out_buf)
    End If
    Return CAL_ERR_UNSUPPORTED
End Process

Process called "calendar_name" takes cal as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a short identifier for the supplied calendar enum value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct switch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns static string constants.
    @End Security_Scope
    If cal is equal to CAL_GREGORIAN:
        Return "Gregorian"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_ISO_8601:
        Return "ISO 8601"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_JULIAN:
        Return "Julian"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_HEBREW:
        Return "Hebrew"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_ISLAMIC_CIVIL:
        Return "Islamic Civil"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_JAPANESE_ERA:
        Return "Japanese Era"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_INDIAN_NATIONAL:
        Return "Indian National"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_CHINESE:
        Return "Chinese"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_COPTIC:
        Return "Coptic"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_ETHIOPIAN:
        Return "Ethiopian"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_PERSIAN:
        Return "Persian"
    End If
    If cal is equal to CAL_BAHAI:
        Return "Bahai"
    End If
    Return "?"
End Process
